Unfortunately, however, today the tone has changed, and the promise of a "more restrained, polite" policy has been forgotten, if ever realized.
It is increasingly striking that the Labour Party does not tolerate divergent views and that all opinions are judged on the basis of whether it is acceptable to the party's leadership.
This trend began shortly after Jeremy became the leader of the couple, and my colleagues, with whom I thought we had a similar political attitude, have recently been increasingly expected to turn my back on my individual opinion and take sides on things that I would otherwise never agree with, whether it was national security issues or the single European market.
After all my public speeches, regardless of what I actually said, they start to insult me on social media, they demand my replacement, they criticize the middle-wing policy, and they tell me that I shouldn't be a member of the Labour Party.
It's not just me.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than many of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are usually limited to politics.
I admire the professionalism and determination of my fellow politicians who are forced to stand up to sexist and racist attacks on a daily basis, but they do not run away.
The most disappointing aspect of today's policy is that attacks at this level have become the norm.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should support a culture of tolerance.
The reality, however, is that we have given up diversity, and with every "untrustful" motion and every amendment to the electoral rules, the circle of tolerance in the party is narrowing.
Over the years, many have advised me to hold back, not be so outspoken, and then "it'll be okay."
That is not why I entered the political field.
32 years ago, as a student, I joined the Labour Party because I was outraged that the Thatcher government had neglected schools so much that our classroom was almost crumbling, and then I fought for better public care for the most deprived as a local councillor and government minister.
I have never concealed my political views, nor have I done otherwise in the last election.
In Nottingham East, it was very clear to everyone what political positions I was taking and on which topics I disagree with the current leadership.
To those who supported the motion on Friday, I would like to say that in this situation, when the country is moving towards a Brexit that will harm not only families, but also companies and public services, I do not understand why I have to spend so much time and energy questioning my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
However, my most important message is not to the members of Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threat of replacement or political purpose will deter me from acting in my own discretion and in the interests of everyone.
Chris Leslie, Nottingham East Representative
