"The sea is ours": Bolivia, without a coast, hopes the court will reopen its path to the Pacific Ocean
Marines patrol around the naval command decorated with sails in La Paz.
There are ocean blue flags on public buildings.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon proclaim the following motto: “We have a right to the sea.
It's our duty to get it back."
Bolivia, without a coast, still has vivid memories of the lost coast, which Chile took in a bloody conflict for resources in the 19th century, and there is a strong desire to rewind the waves of the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may have been the most powerful for many decades, as Bolivia is awaiting the judgment of the International Court of Justice on October 1st, ending five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has the ball, which floods people with a spirit of belonging and peace, who are looking forward to the end in a positive mood,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians are monitoring the decision of the International Court of Justice on projectors, hoping that the Hague Court will stand by Bolivia, and Chile will be obliged to sit at the negotiating table after decades of rapsodic attitude so that Bolivia can have independent access to the sea.
Bolivia’s charismatic, indigenous president, Evo Morales, who faces a controversial battle for next year’s re-election, may lose much with Monday’s verdict.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he said at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court will probably not decide in favour of Bolivia, and that it would not change much if its decision were still favourable to Bolivia.
The UN body in the Netherlands has no authority to judge Chilean territories and has also stipulated in advance that it will not affect the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the judgment of the International Court of Justice was delivered less than six months after the closing speeches indicates that the case was “not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, an expert in international law in Chile.
In addition, the last four years have not only not helped Bolivia's case, but even rejected it.
“The issue of the sea exit has been diverted by the current Bolivian government for its own purposes,” he said.
“Because of Morales’ hostile rhetoric, the rest of Chile’s goodwill has gone away.”
Bolivia and Chile will certainly continue negotiations at some point, but after what has happened, it will be extremely difficult to initiate dialogue.
The two countries have not delegated ambassadors to each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, disagrees with the finding that court decision-making would have been unusually rapid.
Monday brings Bolivia an “exceptional opportunity to open a new chapter in relations with Chile” and a chance to “come out well from the end of 139 years of feud,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, would have used the maritime debate to turn it into a political advantage.
“Bolivia will never give up her right to the Pacific,” he added.
“The judgment gives us the opportunity to see that it’s time to go beyond the past.”
