John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools traditionally provide excellent education. In view of the recent outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed by 2018, which is further strengthened by individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already studying in such institutions, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide students and parents with the best possible services.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers and the position they hold as citizens of the world.
In an educational sector where it is possible to design and introduce customized school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought-after subjects.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language that they understand, it comes to their head.
But if you speak his language, it goes to his heart.”
This is an important reminder, because we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with those from other countries.
This year's exam results show that students from independent schools across the country have produced the best results from foreign languages.
Sixty-eight percent of all students who studied a foreign language achieved a higher A degree (over 85 percent).
According to data collected from the 74 member schools of SCIS, 72 percent of students received higher A degrees in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French and 63 percent of Spanish students reached A degrees.
These results also support the fact that independent schools in Scotland view foreign languages as essential knowledge, the knowledge of which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages have become as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics, both in independent and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Vocational Training Commission found that 17 percent of employers said filling vacant positions was difficult due to lack of language skills.
From this we can see that language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for young people to have a successful career.
As foreign languages are expected in more and more workplaces, language skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career you choose, if you have learned a foreign language, you will gain lifelong knowledge from which you will have a clear advantage.
The ability to communicate directly with other nationalities automatically provides a competitive advantage for multilingual applicants.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents did not speak well enough in any foreign language to get involved with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10% (15%) of respondents.
Therefore, it is important to place emphasis on the language teaching of children.
To speak several languages, especially in the language of developing countries, can be a tool in the hands of children, with which they have a better chance of applying for more important jobs as adults.
Every school in Scotland will have different languages.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while more will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese that are expected to be of paramount importance for the UK by 2020.
Whatever your child’s area of interest, you’ll be able to learn multiple languages at independent schools and be trained by educators who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that will equip and equip them with the skills they will need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
It is not difficult to see that languages remain vital for the future of a country in the current global business environment, and this should be reflected in education.
In fact, knowledge of modern languages should rather be treated as an "international communication skill".
Independent schools offer the choice of diverse and quality education for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire – this is how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
