"No way" for North Korea to unilaterally decommission if it does not trust its negotiating partner
North Korea’s foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that maintaining sanctions only increased distrust of the United States of America, and there is no way that the country would unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Jongho said at the annual General Assembly of the World Organisation that North Korea took "significant and generous steps" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile experiments, closing down the site of nuclear experiments and promising not to expand its nuclear arsenal and the scope of nuclear technology.
“Unfortunately, we do not see similar responses from the Americans,” he said.
“Without confidence in America, we feel that our nation’s security is not assured, and in such circumstances there is no way that we can be one-sided and first-time decommissioned.”
Although Ri reiterated North Korea's disappointment at Washington's opposition to the idea of "staged" nuclear disarmament, according to which North Korea would receive rewards for the steps taken until then, his statement seemed meaningful because he did not clearly reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done so far.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a powerful US President and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12th, during which Kim promised to work on "nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula", while Trump guaranteed North Korea's integrity.
North Korea is trying to make an official point by the end of the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States of America believes that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington did not give in to strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“America insists that we start with nuclear disarmament and that sanctions increase the pressure to impose its will on us, and that it also opposes the declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
The idea that we can be brought to our knees by sanctions is a dream of those who do not know us.
The problem is that non-relieving sanctions only increase our suspicions.”
Ri did not mention that a second summit between Kim and Trump would be planned, but the US president specifically mentioned it at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister pointed out that three meetings took place between Kim and South Korean President Mun Jein in the last five months, and added: “If the country involved in nuclear disarmament were South Korea, not the United States of America, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have reached such a stalemate.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech differed dramatically from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the North American continent with North Korean missiles was inevitable after Trump, "the evil president", called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
This year, at the UN, Trump, who threatened North Korea with “total destruction” last year, praised Kim for having the courage to take steps towards disarmament, but also noted that there is still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions will remain until North Korea implements nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said that no time limit was imposed, i.e. “If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council could reward Pyongyang for the steps taken so far.
On the other hand, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said at the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The sanctions of the Security Council must be adhered to unwaveringly until the actual, final, demonstrable nuclear disarmament has been achieved.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously maintained sanctions against North Korea in order to reduce the financing of Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri during the break of the UN General Assembly and then said that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has been to North Korea three times this year, but his last trip didn't go very well.
After leaving Pyongyang in July, he announced that progress had been made, but North Korea accused him hours later of making "gengsterlike demands".
In the framework of the meeting with Mun this month, North Korea promised to decommission a missile base and a nuclear facility if the United States takes "the right steps."
According to Mun, the "good steps" referred to by Kim would be security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore and steps that could lead to normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students are taught to relax enough.
A new subject at Harvard University this year has encouraged students to sleep more, fighting against the growing macho culture of caffeine-heated all-nighter learning.
An academic has come to the conclusion that students from the world’s number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care about themselves.
The course, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the U.S., was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard Medical College and practices as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
He was encouraged to develop the course by giving a lecture earlier on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only facing this now as a senior?’
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told the Telegraph.
During the course launched for the first time this year, students will be introduced to the fundamental impact of proper sleep habits on their academic and sporting performance, in addition to having a positive impact on their overall well-being.
According to Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical College and director of the university's health service, the university decided to start the course because during the week the students were found extremely sleepless.
The one-hour course also includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a dorm room where students can click on coffee chairs, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleeplessness, and why bedtime routines are important.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
They present a map of the university area with interactive icons to encourage participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that we will not immediately change the behavior of our students.
But we believe they have the right to this knowledge – just as they have the right to be aware of the health effects of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture in which learning a night is a performance continues to flourish, he said, adding that modern technology and the constantly increasing pressure on students result in increasing problems from sleeplessness.
Sufficient and quality sleep is a “secret weapon” of students in the fight against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even protects them from obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain into starving mode and causes a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and biophysics, and last year at Harvard, he took one of the professor's courses as a freshman.
He said that what he heard there opened his eyes and encouraged him to defend the launch of a university-level training.
He hopes that as a next step, postgraduate students will be able to take part in a similar training program before being placed in the competitive sphere.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set a warning for bedtime, a wake-up call for awakening, and learn about the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electric screens and LED light sources, which can easily knock them out of the daily rhythm and make it difficult to fall asleep.
