The new vaccine against cancer can teach the immune system to “see” abnormal cells
The new vaccine against cancer can teach the immune system to “see” and destroy abnormal cells
A vaccine given as part of a treatment will teach the immune system to recognize abnormal cells.
Part of the method is to extract immune cells from the patient and then modify them in a lab.
This is how they can "see" the protein that accompanies a variety of cancers. Treated immune cells are injected back into the patient.
An experimental vaccine has achieved promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who was treated with a vaccine that taught the immune system to recognize abnormal cells could say goodbye to ovarian cancer for more than 18 months.
Part of the method is the extraction of immune cells from the patient; they are modified in the laboratory to "see" a protein called HER2, which is a frequent accompaniment of several cancers; then the replanting of cells.
Jay Berzofsky, professor of American National Cancer Research Institute (Bethesda, Maryland), said: “Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine in our possession.”
HER2 “stimulates the growth of several types of cancer, including breast, ovarian, lung and rectum cancer,” explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar method based on highlighting immune cells and "teaching" them how to attack cancer cells has already been successfully used in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
