What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it managed to reduce poverty?
The annual music event, the Global Citizen Festival, begins on Saturday in New York City. World stars perform at the festival to stand up for a truly noble goal: the global eradication of poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival will be held for the seventh time, and tens of thousands of people are expected to spend the Great Lawn of Central Park, where participants can not only enjoy Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes' performance, but also draw attention to the real purpose of the event: to eliminate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival was first organized in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project. The project is run by an international advocacy group aimed at eradicating poverty by involving more and more people in the active fight against poverty.
Those who undertake certain tasks or “acts” such as volunteering, sending an email to a leading politician, a phone call, or any other meaningful activity with which they can draw attention to the purpose of the project: the eradication of poverty may receive free tickets for the concert.
But how successful has the Global Citizen really been over the past 12 years in achieving the goals set?
Is it really an effective tool to reward people with a concert ticket to convince others of the importance of action, or is it just another form of so-called "clicctivism" when people feel that they have made a meaningful contribution to a case by signing or writing an online petition on Twitter?
Since 2011, according to data from the Global Citizen, more than 19 million "actions" have been carried out by the project supporters, which have served a number of different purposes.
According to the organization, these actions have contributed to the allocation of 37 billion dollars by world leaders to poverty policies and commitments that could affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group claimed that 390 commitments and announcements were from their actions, of which $10 billion had already been paid or collected during fundraising.
The group estimates that the money collected has already directly affected the lives of nearly 649 million people.
The main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a partnership between investors and contractors based in the UK to "help children achieve their potential". The organization promised Rwanda $35 million to help end hunger after receiving more than 4,700 Twitter messages from "global citizens".
“With the support of the UK government and donors, national governments and global citizens like you, social injustice and malnutrition can be banished into the footnotes of history books,” Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition, told the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that after more than 5,000 actions were requested by the UK to improve the nutrition of mothers and their children, the government has earmarked funds for the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve the nutrition of 5 million women and children.
One of the frequently asked questions posted on the Global Citizen website is: “Why do you think extreme poverty can be eradicated?”
According to the Global Citizen’s answer: “It will be a long and difficult journey, in which we sometimes get stuck and sometimes fail.
But like the previous civil rights and anti-segregation movements, we achieve our goal because together we are stronger."
Janet Jackson, Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe will perform at this year's New York event, and the hosts will be Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
