Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee's open source platform Solid.
With Solid, users can choose where they want to store their data and who can access the information.
In his exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was "to gain control of the world".
“We have to do it now,” he said about the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application with Solid's technology allows people to create their own "personal online data warehouse", also known as POD.
This may include lists, to-do lists, calendars, music libraries, and other personal and professional tools.
This is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were available from the same browser at the same time.
In a personal online data warehouse, it is unique that the user can decide in its entirety who has access to his or her data.
The company calls this "implementation of the right of persons to self-determination over data".
John Bruce, CEO of Inrupt, said the company’s mission is to provide resources, processes and the right skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contract developers working in the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using tools available on the Inrupt site.
According to Berners-Lee, he and his team do not ask “Facebook and Google to introduce the technology that brings full change, which would turn the business models of companies completely upside down overnight.”
“We don’t ask permission from them.”
In a post published on Saturday in Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt “is a mission to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the newly built network on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at Massachusetts University of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been involved in debates on the neutrality of the Internet as an important opinion-maker.
Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute, despite the launch of Inrupt.
“I am endlessly optimistic about the next era of the World Wide Web,” Berners-Lee added.
