National Trust investigates the secret life of bats
New research is being carried out on a Scottish-Highland estate to find out how bats exploit the characteristics of the landscape during hunting.
The researchers hope that the results will provide new information on the behaviour of single flying mammals, which may also benefit future species protection initiatives.
Scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will investigate the behavior of common and soprano dwarf bats, as well as brown long-eared bats and water bats in the Inverewe Garden area in Wester Ross.
At the right points in the area, special recording devices are placed to record bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will use hand-held detectors to collect mobile data.
A detailed analysis of the audio material of the recordings can determine the frequency of bat sounds and what species is doing.
Researchers also create a habitat map and report to determine in detail how animals behave depending on the landscape.
Rob Dewar, NTS conservation advisor, hopes that the results will show which habitats are the most important for bats and which species use them.
This information helps to determine the beneficial effects of habitat management work, such as the design of meadows, and how best to preserve forested areas for bats and other affected species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, the size of bat populations has decreased significantly over the last century.
Construction and land development work disrupts animal sleeping areas and reduces their living space.
Wind turbines and street lighting are also a risk factor for them, as are fly papers placed out, certain chemical processes used for building materials, as well as attacks on domestic cats.
Bats aren't really completely blind.
Because of their night predatory nature, however, they rely much more on their hearing when hunting prey than on their sight.
Based on the reflection of ultrasound, they can determine the exact position of insects and landmarks on their way.
The NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
They work with ten qualified professionals who regularly conduct studies and sleep-place tests and sometimes participate in rescue work.
