In 1996, a tsunami hit West Donggala, and nine people died.
Indonesia is located in the geologically active Pacific Ring of Fire, which is why earthquakes are common.
Just a few of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On December 26, a huge sea quake began on the west coast of the province of Aceh in North Sumatra, which launched a tsunami reaching 14 countries, which claimed a total of 226,000 lives along the Indian Ocean coast, and more than half of the victims died in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong quakes shook the western coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias near Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 quake shook the southern part of Java, Indonesia's largest island, and the tsunami that followed it claimed almost 700 victims on the south coast.
2009: An earthquake of 7.6 destroyed near Padang, the capital of Western Sumatra Province.
