Red tide news: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, more stained flowering has been reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentration.
The extent of the red tide is about 130 miles of coast, from Pinellas in the north to Lee counties in the south.
There are spots about 10 miles outside Hillsborough County, but compared to last week, there are relatively smaller areas.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported in and off Pinellas County, low to high concentrations along Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County and off the coast, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in Lee County and off the coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There were still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation from northwest Florida was reported last week.
